{"parse":{"title":"Parfilage","pageid":55460327,"revid":807711517,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Parfilage</b> was a fashionable <a href=\"/wiki/Pastime\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Pastime\">pastime</a> among women at the <a href=\"/wiki/Palace_of_Versailles\" title=\"Palace of Versailles\">Versailles</a> in the 1760s and 1770s. While most forms of ladies' handwork involved making something, parfilage was the opposite: women spent their time unraveling gold and silver braid, lace, or <a href=\"/wiki/Epaulets\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Epaulets\">epaulets</a>. As the fad grew--<a href=\"/wiki/Friedrich_Melchior,_Baron_von_Grimm\" title=\"Friedrich Melchior, Baron von Grimm\">Grimm</a>'s <i>Correspondence litt\u00e9raire</i> referred to a \"furor\" for it in winter 1773<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>--ornaments were made and sold solely for the purpose of being unmade. Ladies carried small sacks with them for the gold and silver threads they had salvaged. Taken to a goldsmith, the thread could be melted down and made into coins. In Britain, parfilage was sometimes known as \"drizzling.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Parfilage&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Grimm, Melchior (1829\u20131831). <i>Correspondance litt\u00e9raire</i>. Furne.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Correspondance+litt%C3%A9raire&amp;rft.pub=Furne&amp;rft.date=1829%2F1831&amp;rft.aulast=Grimm&amp;rft.aufirst=Melchior&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AParfilage\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\nHelen Clifford, \"A Commerce with Things: The Value of Precious Metalwork in early modern England,\" in Maxine Berg and Helen Clifford, eds., <i>Consumers and Luxury: Consumer Culture in Europe, 1650-1850</i>  (Manchester University Press, 1999).</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Parfilage&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://kickshawproductions.com/blog/?p=11240\">Parfilage (drizzling)</a>--costume history blog</li></ul>\n<p><br />\n</p>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/75/Signorina_in_viola.svg/19px-Signorina_in_viola.svg.png\" width=\"19\" height=\"31\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/75/Signorina_in_viola.svg/29px-Signorina_in_viola.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/75/Signorina_in_viola.svg/38px-Signorina_in_viola.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"255\" data-file-height=\"412\" /></td><td><i>This <a href=\"/wiki/Fashion\" title=\"Fashion\">fashion</a>-related article is a <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Stub\" title=\"Wikipedia:Stub\">stub<